5000|$|A {{bonus issue}} is usually {{based upon the}} number of shares that {{shareholders}} already own. [...] (For example, the bonus issue may be [...] "n shares for each x shares held"; but with fractions of a share not permitted.) While the <b>issue</b> <b>of</b> <b>bonus</b> <b>shares</b> increases {{the total number of}} shares issued and owned, it does not change the value of the company. Although the total number of issued shares increases, the ratio of number of shares held by each shareholder remains constant. In this sense, a bonus issue is similar to a stock split.|$|E
